description.narrative:
Project goal: evaluate governance, key processes and internal control system, examine financial statements; provide recommendations and step-by step roadmap for further transformation of NPBU on the way to becoming and efficient and competitive public broadcasting organization. 
Objectives:
1) Evaluate governance and provide recommendations for its improvement based on leading practices;
2) Examine key processes and procedures; identify areas for improvement in terms of efficiency and effectiveness;
3) Analyze HR activities, policies and practices, behaviors, risks and internal controls; 
4) Validate the financial statements as at 31 December 2017 and for the period then ended (including the opening balances).

The new public broadcasting system was established on the basis of 31 national and regional formerly state-controlled TV and radio broadcasters, which were united in 2017 and became NPBU. The audit held at the entry stage of this important media reform assessed the governance, organisational structure, human resources and process management as inherited from the predecessor state broadcasting system. As a result, EY developed a three-year Roadmap of transformations – the set of recommendations and a timetable of recommended organisational transformations (short-, mid- and long-term). In summer 2018 this Roadmap was operationalized by the NPBU Management Board and Supervisory Board, with the view to transform NPBU into an efficient and sustainable media organisation. This Roadmap is also being used now as guidance by the donors working with the public broadcasting reform in Ukraine (e.g. Internews Network, DWA, Council of Europe).
The first financial audit held by a credible international auditor EY became the foundation for further accounting reform of the National Public Broadcaster in line with international standards. Based on EY audit recommendations, NPBU managed to successfully align their accounting with IFRS already in 2018, which was confirmed as a result of 2018 independent audit. 
Unplanned, but important result: Based on EY financial audit opinion, the stocks of the public joint stock company NPBU were issued by the state registrar in October 2018, completing a legal process of establishing the national public broadcaster.
The organizational audit had two deliverables:
1) detailed report on findings;
2) comprehensive roadmap of NPBU transformation for the use of Supervisory Board, Management Board and other parties engaged in the public broadcasting reform and NPBU operations.
Both the report and the Roadmap were duly and timely developed in a high-quality multi-stakeolder consultation process.  The Steering Committee including EY team, NPBU senior management and the Embassy representatives was involved at the design stage, progress reporting, validation and finalization of the findings. This ensured strong ownership of the audit recommendations within NPBU at relevant levels, and their further rigorous implementation. 
The first stage of implementing the audit recommendations already brough noticeable changes to the company: 
- unnecessary layers of responsibility and unclear delegations of power were eliminated, new organizational structure of the company was approved by the Supervisory Board;
- a system of recruiting and adapting new employees was launched, staff evaluation system was put in place;
- new collective agreement was introduced;
- an internal audit service was established and started working;
- anti-corruption function was added (appointment of an anti-corruption commissioner, approval of the anti-corruption program);
- a number of policies and regulations were developed (compliance policy, accounting policy, transparency policy, code of ethics, information partnership policy, strategy for the development of broadcasting networks, etc.);
- legislative solutions for modernization of governance and internal control were developed. 
The expected, and a number of unexpected results were achieved. Among some unexpected results in a broader context is replication of this project's approach to other large-scale institutional reforms (i.e. Pension Fund, Prosecutor's Office. The Embassy provided reference letters to EY for participating in these initiatives). 
At the impact level it would be also sensible to take stock of the progress when the full 2018-2021 Roadmap of Transformation would be implemented.
